  "prompt": "Why can't planets be different shapes?",
  "response": "Planets tend to be spherical due to a concept called **hydrostatic equilibrium**. Here's a breakdown:\n\n*   **Gravity's Role:** A planet's own gravity pulls everything towards its center. This force acts equally in all directions.\n\n*   **Mass Matters:** If an object has enough mass (generally agreed upon as 10^20 kg), the gravity will be strong enough to overcome the object's own structural strength (like its rockiness or ice).\n\n*   **Hydrostatic Equilibrium:** When gravity overpowers structural strength, the object starts to deform. The material flows and adjusts until it reaches a state where the gravitational force is balanced by the internal pressure. This balanced state is what we call hydrostatic equilibrium.\n\n*   **Sphere is the Natural Shape:** The shape that minimizes gravitational potential energy is a sphere. In other words, a sphere is the most \"efficient\" way for all that mass to be distributed under the influence of its own gravity. Every particle is as close to the center as it can be on average.\n\n*   **Smaller Objects:** Smaller objects, like asteroids or small moons, don't have enough gravity to achieve hydrostatic equilibrium. Their structural strength is sufficient to resist the pull of gravity, so they can have irregular shapes.\n\n*   **Rotation Can Cause Bulging:** A rapidly rotating planet can bulge at its equator because of centrifugal force. For example, Earth is slightly flattened at the poles and bulges at the equator due to its rotation. But even with this bulge, it's still essentially spherical.\n\n**In summary:** The combination of significant mass and gravity forces planets into a roughly spherical shape because that's the most stable configuration under those conditions.\n",
